        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p>Dear Sir!</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I thank you for a copy of your Bible. It<lb/> is indeed a handsome
                edition. I am sorry that it came too<lb/> late to be noticed by me in the
                Introduction<lb/> p. XV, which was printed before your Bible came to my<lb/> hands.
                Still I shall notice it in its proper place.</p>
            <p><persName>Dr. Huerst</persName> of <placeName>Leipzig</placeName> has (in his
                Bibliotheca Judaica)<lb/> betrayed a profound ignorance of American literature.</p>
            <p>So he wrote</p>
            <p><persName>Isaac Leeser</persName> (Pr. in <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>); The
                Occident (Eine<lb/> Monatsschrift für jüd. Intressen). III. Jahrgänge.<lb/>
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
                <date>1843-46</date>.8.</p>
            <p>He not only forgot to mention your own books, but<lb/> also those which you edited. I
                called his attention to<lb/> this and other facts, and he desired me to give
                him<lb/> correct statements in regard to <placeName>America</placeName>. Please<lb/>
                send me a list of your own books and those<lb/> edited by you, together with the
                necessary dates.</p>
            <p>I believe my friend <persName>Kalisch</persName> is with you in
                    <placeName>Ph.</placeName> I pray<lb/> you to encourage him; he is too much of
                an <add>עניו</add> and<lb/> needs cheering up, if we are to expect something great
                of<lb/> him.</p>
            <p>I send you the first volume of my history by mail<lb/> because this is the cheapest
                way. If you should think<lb/> it worth while to <sic>criticise</sic> it, I will call
                your attention<lb/> to the passages in it which are new, and therefore<lb/> exposed
                to criticism.</p>
            <p>1. The distinction between history and religion. Introd. XV.</p>
            <p>2. The death of <persName>Jacob</persName> p 35. 36.</p>
            <p>3. The title of the Israelites to the land of <placeName>Canaan</placeName> p 37 to
                40. 110.</p>
            <p>4. Identity of the Anakims with Manetha's Hyksas<add>?</add>, who<lb/> were the
                oppressors of <placeName>Israel</placeName> in <placeName>Egypt</placeName> p.
                41-54</p>
            <p>5. Exposition of the Decalogue p. 80-84</p>
            <p>6. The <sic>defence</sic> of <persName>Joshua</persName>
                <sic>p</sic> 213-216</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>7. Chronological position of the administration<lb/> of <persName>Samson</persName>
                and <persName>Jephtah</persName> p. 234. 265 to 269., which<lb/> makes new the whole
                period of Judges.</p>
            <p>8. The <sic>highschool</sic> at <placeName>Ramah</placeName> 250-256.</p>
            <p>9. Chronological investigation on <persName>David's</persName> seven<lb/> years in
                    <placeName>Hebron</placeName>324</p>
            <p>10. Reconciliation of <persName>I. Samuel</persName> 16.17. 18308</p>
            <p>11. The wars of <persName>David</persName>337-344</p>
            <p>12. The revolt under and after <persName>Solomon</persName>377-384</p>
            <p>Almost the whole history of the Kings is new, having<lb/>
                <sic>reconciliated</sic>
                <persName>Samuel</persName>, Kings, and Chronicles, and<lb/> having compared
                scriptural passages with the<lb/> late discoveries in <placeName>Nineveh</placeName>
                xc.</p>
            <p>The four appendices are totally new. I have established<lb/> that
                    <persName>moses</persName> wrote the Pentateuch, that this law and<lb/> religion
                was the code of the nation in all ages, which<lb/> was most emphatically negatived
                by modern critics; that<lb/> the historical books were written much earlier than<lb/>
                <persName>Jost</persName> and others believed; that art and science flourished<lb/>
                among the ancient Israelites; and that they were thoroughly<lb/> democratic and
                invincible patriots. In religion I have<lb/> not only rushed many a hypercritical
                assertion; but<lb/> also the grand supposition, that the prophets did not<lb/>
                understand Judaism until <persName>Jesus</persName> came to expound it.<lb/> The
                faults you will find, and I am ready to hear<lb/> them.</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Most Respectfully</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Yours</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">
                <persName role="author">Isaac M. Wise</persName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>Albany</placeName>
                <date>December 7. 5614</date>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">
                <date>1854</date>
            </p>
